text: The "world design" looks great, and the casting looks promising, but I hope the trailer doesn't represent the movie. I think they should try to replicate (hihi) the atmosphere of the first movie, and they can't do that with a lot of explosions and action shots. I fear they will try to cram too much content into the movie, and they will not take their time for slow scenes accompanied with quiet dialog, or just plain silence with the audience have to imagine what the characters are thinking. I don't want this to be an epic hero story where the world is saved, but rather a quiet conflict resolved in the shadows. A detective story, with a lot of philosophy and intersting dialog,  which might as well be played out in our own world, but is instead set in this amazing dystopian future.

author: Walt Kowalski

text: This film will be awful. The trailer gives it away, Die Hard in the future with Harrison Ford and Ryan Gosling and a truck load of sci-fi and action film cliche's from the last decade. What was great about Bladerunner was that it broke a lot of conventions and went a new route. This film just rehashes the same, tired old sequences from other films like the new Star Wars and will be instantly forgettable. I would like to be wrong. However, Denis Villeneuve is an okay director, okay. Arrival is okay, not great. Sicario is okay, it could have been great, but is okay. The original Blade Runner did not need explosions, it was a film noire, an existential sci-fi. This one looks anything but. Cliche's? More CGI than you can shake a GPU at. Denis Villeneuve admitted on the Arrival blueray commentary that Sci-Fi is tough and he struggles, so I respect him for that. This is not his film. Ridley Scott did have a say in this film, and if you noticed, he is not that great lately.

text: This looks beautiful. So glad the aesthetic doesn't look like the big CG garbage fest I was fearing. The only thing I worry about is the film score. How could anyone replicate the musical brilliance of Vangelis? His treatment was so integral to the original that it became just as iconic as the visuals and the film itself. Even if you hired someone as accomplished as John Williams to do the score, he wouldn't be able to match (let alone surpass) the brooding, synth heavy, haunting atmosphere created by Vangelis' pieces. Please treat the production of the film's sound with as much respect as you pay the rest of the movie because it's just as important to the cinematic experience.

text: It looks great visually and would probably make a good action movie but this looks like a terrible Blade Runner follow up. Blade Runner is not an action movie. This movie has wayyyy too much conventional sci-fi action in it. What I loved about the original film was  the dialogue and the character interactions. The atmosphere and the music only elevated what was going on onscreen. Perhaps the most memorable scenes for me were the parts where it was just two characters talking to one another. This looks like an action movie masquerading as a Blade Runner sequel. Plus it's weird seeing a bright sky and the holograms that look more like 'Ghost in the Shell' and less Blade Runner. You don't need amazing special effects to make a good Blade Runner film, what you need is a good script and I never ever bought that Deckard is a replicant crap. I'd rather have seen a spiritual successor w/o Harrison Ford than a direct sequel. Blade Runner was perfect as it was. Also nothing will ever top Roy Batty as the "villain".

text: It's scary to think about the continuation of this movie. Much of the fascination of the original film came from Philip K. Dick's scorn for scientific rigor. He was only interested in discussing the human soul.  The original story, both in the book and in the movie, bragged about discussing what "human being" is. We left the cinema thinking about what defines a human being. The film sent and recovered the old Aristotelian metaphysics in which one tries to find the essence of things. Blade Runner made me wonder when I was 18.  The atmosphere that was built by Scott was as absurd as the creation of artificial humans that Dick invented. These two things, lulled by the electronic music of Vangelis interspersed with romantic melodies lost in the midst of the urban chaos, which was only surpassed by aerial views of the city, caused a strangeness in the spectator.  Blade Runner may even work, but I believe it will be necessary to switch philosophy for action and more action (action only). The pieces of music that appear in the trailler are a bit disappointing. At least until now, no memorable melody is perceived and the percussion is exaggerated, giving the impression that it will be just another action movie. text: Refuse to watch this - It looks like heretical junk in every respect.  Maybe I'm just nostalgic or old-school, but I'm not interested in trendy actors and over-baked plots. Just look at it - It's got all the hallmarks of cheap imitation, meant as a commercial cash grab. Full of fake CGI and shallow characters. Too fast, too overwhelming, too forced, not enough love or personality to it.  Blade Runner was an Original that cannot be replicated (intended) - A saudade meditation and study in cyberpunk atmosphere lovingly crafted through deliberate slow pacing, careful visual design (Syd Mead), pain-staking perspective shots, old-school special effects (Douglas Trumbull), and analog synth-wave meant to mimic orchestral movements, done by a master (Vangelis). It created a sense of beautiful loneliness, isolation, and melancholy, of a living breathing futuristic city, a Neo-Tokyo. You could smell the rain and neon in every scene. It created an emotional depth greater than the sum of its production parts.  Moreover, the actors were participants who spoke little, and their dialogue left space to breathe in between sentences, allowing the viewer to soak up each scene. The underlying theme was that they were dealing with an existential crisis bigger than themselves - what it means to be human, a sentient being with limited lifespan, and the right to live. There was no-one to blame, no real enemy - almost a tragedy of sorts. And yet they could have been anyone on the street - you or me.   I'll leave you with this - to "get" what Blade Runner is all about, what I'm talking about here - One only needs listen to Vangelis' Blade Runner Blues, while keeping the spectacular visuals in mind. It is truly one of a kind Sci-Fi Noir movie that was inspired by the culture and technology of decade it lived in (1980s), and its vision of the future still echoes with us today. I highly doubt this sequel can live up to it, and nor should it - You don't mess with a classic.

The original had this griminess to it that made it stand out from the other Sci-Fi films of the time and even now. This one just looks like your standard big budgeted Sci-Fi action film with a heavy emphasis on CG. I feel like this is relying more on the technology to "improve" the visuals and look instead of letting the actors, scenery, and the story itself tell it. To me, it's like what happened when the remake of 'Little House On The Prairie' came out some years ago (I know this is a sequel but bare with me) as while it was a good remake and a entertaining watch, it lost what made the original series great, which was, again, the dirty look and how it actually felt like a real location while the remake felt too clean with it's visuals and I fear this is what's going on with this movie. Will I still see this movie? Probably as it does look like a good movie but I'm just not a fan of this films look and overall cleanliness to it.

text: Everybody throughout history ate bread; Stone Age man ate bread, the Greeks ate bread, the Romans ate bread, even the Vikings ate bread. But they all had different ways of making it and used different ingredients.  Stone Age Man was probably the first to make bread about 7,000 years ago, but not the kind we eat today. the theory is that whilst out hunting for meat they may have collected wild grains, crushing them between big stones and added water to make a thick gruel. Next, at some point, they started to heat this gruel on hot stones into thick flat cakes, the first bread was baked!. 'Now that's a good idea', they thought, "if we collect all the wild grain we can and store it we can make these thick flat cakes whenever we want, even in the winter!' Soon they had another great idea. They realised that If they collected the wild grain seed and planted it near their cave they wouldn't have to wander around looking for it. Plus they soon discovered that once planted it kept coming back every year- even better! This changed the way Stone Age Man lived his live. No longer did they live as Nomadic tribes (wandering tribes looking for meat) they settled down, formed settlements or villages and became farmers. You could say that Bread helped invent civilisation, how cool is that!  Until Egyptian times bread was 'unleavened'. This means that it was flat bread like the naan or pitta bread we eat today. It was 4,000 years ago that the Egyptians discovered a kind of yeast to add to the dough called 'Barn', to make bread 'leavened' or risen. We can see loafs of bread from this time in the British Museum that look similar to the ones we eat today, but I wouldn't like to make a piece toast out of one! The Egyptians invented a process to grind the grains into a course flour, but it was the Romans who developed the idea of grinding or milling the grain and then sieving it to make fine flour. Their milling process used two large flat stones, the bottom stone stayed in one position and the top stone rotated - this is still the basis of the technique we use today! The Romans brought this system of bread making to all the lands they conquered. Thanks, Maximus Buttius!  The Romans and Greeks loved bread. They liked to make lots of different breads, experimenting with the shapes and adding fruits, spices & honey. They had bakeries in those times too. One kind was for poor people who would bring the bread dough they had prepared at home and have the baker bake it into a finished loaf. Bakers were very important in Roman times, they were the only craftsmen to have freedom of the city and not be considered slaves. They even had their own Bakers Guild called Collegium Pistorium. But such privileges did have their drawbacks, Bakers and their children could never be anything but bakers and they weren't allowed to go to the amphitheatre to see the Gladiators. We have a Guild of Bakers in England today called The Worshipful Company of Bakers, but I'm sure they'd be allowed to go to the theatre if they wanted too!  Vikings and Normans also ate a lot of bread, usually made from rye and qat grains instead of wheat. The Normans sometimes made a large flat loaf which they used as a plate for their dinner, these were called Trenchers. Does that mean if they were very hungry they would eat their plates too? What a great idea!

text: Why did they have to put Michael Bay-esque explosions in this? Blade Runner was never an action movie, it was a neo-noir thriller-mystery set in a sci fi universe. I hate to come off as some movie elitist but I pray the large scale action scenes are kept to the bare minimum. It really doesn't suit the tone or style of the original at all.  Not to mention the continuity issues by¬†having Deckard in this new Blade Runner in the first place. The entire ambiguity of whether Deckard was a replicant himself, something Ridley Scott has¬†continually alluded to, is almost certainly ruined¬†now. The whole point of the original was the themes of existentialism and¬†the¬†meaning of being human, and whether you know you're human or not. It made you ask these types of questions, and¬†it looks as though the new movie will almost nullify some of what¬†made the original such a great piece of cinema. ¬†¬†  The positives I'm finding are the cinematography, which looks very good. The world looks dense and well crafted. Also, Ryan Gosling tends not to sign up for movies with bad scripts and is probably the only actor around at the moment¬†that could pull a main role off in a Blade Runner movie. I hope it's good, it's just the trailer isn't filling me with much hope.

text: Does anyone in Hollywood even bother to watch the Original Material or find out what its about?  Apparently not.  Blade Runner isn't about slaves and conspiracies.  WTF is the crap about society being built by slaves?  Is that some black power fantasy?  Societies like this are built by industries.  Look at the robots!  Why would you need replicants when you have all those robots?  Replicants have memories and have feelings.  This isn't necessary to build stuff with.  They are used for Supersoldiers and Sex. Hollywood is full of crap.  This movie is not even similar to the Original Cyberpunk Classic that started the Cyberpunk genre.  This is the same old Hollywood agenda with some cheap nostalgia thrown in.  Since Rachel won't even be in this film cause Sean Young lost her mind, there isn't even a reason to make this thing. Finding out if Rachel had an expiration date, and whether Deckard was a replicant was the ONLY REASON anyone wanted a sequel.  Without Rachel and with Deckard being in his 70s, this film is pointless and just the same old Hollywood crap.

Clothings the same, music slightly more black now these days but pretty much the same, life styles the same, politics the same, cities are the same no hive city with technology and all that bullcrap, no holograms, no humanoid robot servants, no flying cars or levitating skateboards. only thing thats different is the internet thats all. So stop with these movies about how 50 years from now things are going to be this and that. text: On introspection, now, I know why this feels foreign.  What is completly different with this to the orginal: it is the absence of Syd Mead and his desings, it is the seemingly vast, open and unlimited space - the original was always shot in close quarters in this overcrowded environment which made you feel very tense just by virtue of being claustrophobic.  Syd's designs made the movie look futuristic, comic like, but yet real at the same time, because it oozed authenticity and functionality. The props were very carefully chosen as well. Everything in the scene had purpose and it worked.  Then comes the filming crew. The lighting and shadowing. My my...this 2049, by the looks of it has nothing on the original. Not close at all. Whoever did the cinematography on the original, please come from the other world back, these guys can't do it with all the advances of the technology.  Also, Vangelis. Vangelis and his piercing score. And Sean Young of course. And Rutger Hauer. Also Joanna Cassidy and of course Daryl Hannah. I guess, I just wanted the original look and feel ( with all the grit and grunge ) cast and filmed in 80s to be shown. Not this. We lost the way to reproduce things from the past.  Overall, it is sad that we can not have the sort of movie the first one was. Even though, supposedly, the technology has advanced light years ahead from 80s we still can not reproduce best things from the past. I guess this is how civilizations and cultures perish. Lore and methods are lost and there is no way back.

text: The more I sit and review and wait in anticipation of Blade Runner 2049 the more I realize the original Blade Runner was not actually about Deckard (Harrison Ford) ... it was about Roy(Rutger Hauer)   "Do androids dream of electric sheep ... do androids have a soul" a question answered in prose by Roy in saying " I've seen things you people wouldn't believe ..." and captured in the poetry of the ending "all those things will be lost when I die ... like tear drops in rain"   The release of the dove symbolized the 21 grams of matter that some say the soul weighs ... "Do androids dream of electric sheep ... do androids have a soul".  Rutger Hauer in writing and acting this stole the scene from Harrison Ford and made what was going to be a good movie a great movie. Rutger Hauer made  what was going to be "artistic" ... "art".    Who in Blade Runner 2049 will be Rutger Hauer. Who will connect it to us. Who will give this movie a soul.

text: My prediction: Ryan Gosling is the offspring of Deckard, who is revealed not to be a Replicant, and Rachel, who is the first and only Replicant with the capacity to reproduce. Rachel's corpse is the "Key" to which Jared Leto's character is referring as he wishes to instill this capacity in the Replicants which he manufactures as by his own admission he "Can only make so many". Finding Rachel's corpse and examining her DNA will allow him to proliferate the Replicant population and build his empire on their backs.  The "Wall" between between Replicants and humans to which Robin Wright's character refers is thereby broken by Ryan Gosling, as he is both human and Replicant. Although it seems illogical that such a discovery will cause war. Walls separate and divide people, thus causing warfare and violence, while bridging walls precipitates harmony and peace. So if this is the twist, which it seems like it is, then the writers really fucked up with where they're going with this narrative.

text: I went into this theater not knowing a single thing about blade runner. All I knew was that this movie had ryan gosling, harrison ford, and jared leto in it. And I am beyond pleasantly surprised. It was an incredible movie. And watching the trailers now, I realized they don't really show you what this movie is about. And _that's_ how all trailers should be. You get a sense for the movie, but you shouldn't know what it's about so that you're more immersed in the storyline when you watch it for the first time. I wish more trailers were like this one.  Loooved the movie!!

text: It is the perfect sequel to a jewel that did not need any sequel. I just watched it. I look forward to watch it 3 or 4 more times to "get it better". And I watched the original one well over 200 times ... I'm not the only one apparently :-) Both are rare masterpieces of art cinematography, in a genre filled with bad blockbusters. Yes indeed 2001 A Space Odyssey is a good movie, so are The Matrix ¬ß Interstellar, The Andromeda Strain ¬ß Ex Machina (etc...). But none of those have such a magical photography, perfect soundtrack (especially Blade Runner), top quality acting, every detail so masterfully crafted ¬ß presenting you some of the most important subjects a human being could get into, and leave you with decades of questionning after having watched them... Both of those movies set the trends, others follow... I wonder what Denis Villeneuve is going to do with Dune :-) Most probably an instant classic science fiction masterpiece...We'll see... To my opinion, Blade Runner ¬ß Blade Runner 2049 stand above any other science fiction/anticipation movie, and each of them is the ultimate sf masterpiece of its generation...      But that's just me, officer A speaking ...

text: We can't get the basic biomechanics of human motion right in an anthropoid robot and they want us to believe 'actors are replicants!'.    Bwuahahahahaah.  Only bwave gnu wurldurs get grumpy about a capabiity that doesn't exist because...replacement with the Other is cool paranoia.  Just like the original, more art film flim flam than substantive scifi.  Remember folks:  the purpose of science fiction, what separated it from the horror genre` it was originally a subset of, was and remains HUMAN reactions to the new and strange.  If you enact a fear based plot constraint to actor responses ('We're being hunted!') you limit the horizon by which the S2F2 can bring you to different understandings.  Hence schlock for it's own sake.  We live in a ruined biosphere but boy do we make pretty 'bots which are waaaay better than us.  Interact with that? Nope.  Just react to it.  Show a movie wherein robots are dumb.  Have no minds.  And yet are able to repeat motions like an industrial tool and move with the precision of the finest diamond cutter.  Then show what happens when humans either adopt or adapt to this level of enhanced labor force, and the world changes because humans no longer have to live within  class controlled resource environment which they can only generate two hands, one back, one brain worth of labor.  The elites control the production and process side of things.  But robots will let the working class keep societies' cogs turning without yielding the 'field manager' requirement for personal supervision.  Letting the working poor gain their own station, on sheer work product multiplication of intrinsic worth.  THAT would be an interesting human vs. human story.  Homocidal sextoys and warbots?  Not so much.

text: When Deckard said Rachael was special, he wasn't kidding. Director Denis Villeneuve does a commendable attempt to pay tribute to the first movie, but that's like trying to make Citizen Kane II. Like the original, it's a visually intense movie, but each scene is not a work of art per the original.  The sound track is heavy and disjointed in spots, and spot on in others. Acting across the board is excellent, even if Gosling still not my first choice, he's solid. If this movie falls short anywhere compared to the original, it's in the dialogue. The original had dialogue I still repeat in my head once in a while, whereas this movie, I can't think of a single scene that will stick in my head. The evil genius in this movie is more a side character, unlike Tyrell, who was one of the most compelling characters in the original.   The movie both pays pays homage to the original, with some characters and scenes being very reminiscent to the first, and many original to this film. By this review one might think I didn't enjoy 2049, but that's not the case at all. This is a must see movie for fans of the original if for no other reason you get to immerse yourself in all things Blade Runner for almost three hours. I don't think it really added anything to the story per se, but it's one of the better movies I have seen in some time, and any time a thinking person's sci-fi movie is made, must be applauded. This one gets an A.

text: What an amazing film. A masterpiece of atmosphere, mood, cinematography, sound effects and story with great performances all around the board, and that asks questions that'll leave you pondering for a while. It kinda annoys me that so many people hate on it, but at the same time, people didn't like 2001: A space odyssey when that first came out for similar reasons, (Too slow, too long) and now it's one of the most beloved movies of all time and considered to be one of, if not the, best sci-fi movie of all time. I'm sure this movie will receive the same treatment, and that it'll get more appreciation with time and will be considered a classic in the future.   Plus I'd rather have a film that takes risks and asks questions than one that plays it safe and try to appeal as much as they can to mass audiences without taking any risks, like those marvel or star wars movies. This is not to say I don't like star wars and Marvel movies, only this is on another level altogether. (Or at least for the new star wars films, empire is still one of my faves.)

text: This trailer really doesn't do the movie justice. This makes it look like some generic action sci-fi movie that just happens to be set in the same universe as Blade Runner - in other words, a cheap cash-in on the first movie's popularity.   I saw Blade Runner 2049 the other day and it couldn't be further from the truth - this movie is a fantastic love letter to the original movie and really does feel like a legit sequel in every way. The movie is very slow and in this case that's a good thing - Blade Runner was an incredibly slow movie. It's visually stunning like the original Blade Runner, and just like the original Blade Runner the story is a Detective Film Noir story that just happens to be set in the future. The only action sequences in the entire movie are the ones shown in this trailer - usually that's a negative but in the case of a Blade Runner sequel that's a huge positive.   Blade Runner 2049 actually compliments the first Blade Runner as a sequel is _meant_ to, instead of being a complete departure in terms of style, tone and story that actually contradicts the original movie (I'm looking at you, Prometheus...)

text: The general audience for this movie really does seem to be split between people who thought that it was a waste of time, and people who thought that it was a truly rare and amazing masterpiece.  I think that it is one of those movies where, if you can get into it, then it just _works_, and you come out wishing it was longer. But if you can't get into it, then you just see a lot of scenes that are far too long with the story not evolving enough throughout.  I personally thought it was a legitimately really good film, with  heaps of new ideas, amazing cinematics, and just over-all awesomeness.  Too bad I can only express my love for this movie virtually, as everyone who watched this movie that I really know kind of hated it.  I think the problem to that solution if just getting some new friends hahaha

text: Fuck the box office figures. The majority of people who watch movies these days have the attention span of a gnat. So consumed by their need for approval on social media its wasted on them and thats why it hasn't performed well. For those of us who absolutely fucking love this film for its story, breathtaking cinematography and just overall fucking awsomeness, we will carry as much respect for this film as we do for Ridley Scott's original. Blade Runner 2049 will be still watched, discussed and debated about in 25 - 30 years time just like the first one, while the so called blockbusters will go and not come back and be forgotten about. Respect, love and a cult following to keep it going through generations is worth more than box office figures. Everyone who was involved with this film should be proud of it.

author: Blade Runner

text: The film tries to impress us with its connection to the original, when in fact it just cannibalizes the Ridley Scott masterpiece for the only value it has. It's just not organically woven into the new film and it's painfully obvious, right down to the 'imitation Vangelis' soundtrack which is so bad it should be illegal. 2049 has no depth and dimension and points to the work of a very mediocre director re-configuring and dispensing the bland expectations of a 21st century sci-fi audience who are so dumbed-down by 21st century schlock by now that they, sadly, can't tell the difference. I had to keep telling myself that the film had nothing to do with the original just to get through, but then I was left with the stark, 2-dimensionality of a truly poor work that relies on its visual effects and darkest themes to anesthetize the audience into believing they actually saw something worthwhile.

text: Top ten actors of all time 1. Gary Oldman- the most versatile actor in film history from Leon the professional to the Dark knight Oldman is unrecognizable 2. Robert De Niro- the only actor to play in pretty much every movie that built modern Hollywood. The Godfather part 2, Taxi Driver, Goodfellas, and Raging Bull. And if course "your talking to me?" 3. Philip Seymour Hoffman- never a celebrity that he deserved to be, Hoffman who ODed on heroin a few years ago was one of the most powerful actors ever. He could play the biggest "klutz" in Maganolia and a charismatic cult leader in The Master, Hoffman's dynamic acting style never was and never will be. 4. Edward Norton- the king of dystopian genre. Nortons mono tone voice in Fight Club helped Finchers classing become the greatest dystopian film ever. Norton also had an unforgettable role in American History X where he plays a ruthless skin head attempting to repent. Nortan taps into our dark feelings he's the dark whisper in our ears. 5. Hearh Ledger- he didn't play in much because he died yo soon. But ledger revolutionized what it meant to give it all you got. In the Dark Knight his potrayal of the Joker made us urinate in our popcorn. Will never see something like him again! 6. Al Pacino- "say hello to my little friend!".This dude dominated the big screen for three decades and played the effing Godfather. He went from being the cold calculated Michael Corleone to the impulsive sociopath Tony Montana. 7.Jimmy Stewart-  before Brando took the crown of Hollywood legend their was this guy. Stewart aka Goerge Bailey represented the true American for two decades. He's always the lone righteous guy standing up against the overwhelming evil. Nobody knows but he also played in a lot of westerns where he proved he wasn't just a great actor, but he also knew how to be a gun slinger. 8. Marlon Brando- "I coulda been a contender", Brando was right if he hadn't turned down every movie offer. Although he played in a lot of crap his few explosive roles earned him the title "greatest actor of all time". He's attributed for bringing "realism" to acting, it's hard to say if that's true but one thing for sure Vito Corleone is bad ass. 9. Kevin Spacey- he may be a fucking sicko but he was the king of the screen for two decades. Playing in films such as seven, the usual suspects and American beauty Spacey has become an icon. He makes us squirm laugh and piss. He's just the god damn Ralph Underwood of movies motherfuckas. 10. Leonardo DiCaprio- the greatest actor of the 21st century DiCaprios diverse roles leaves our mouths hanging open. From playing teen sensation Jack in Titanic to Cobb in Inception DiCaprio carries on the torch of De Niro, Pacino, and Brando

text: two things that I will regret for entire life: 1)  my dog got sick and he opened his eyes all night looking at me (I put him in my bed so I can look after him) in the night before he passed away the next day. I didn't realise that he was saying goodbye thought he was just sick and I didn't hug him enough that night. I wish I could have done that. I would give anything to have him back in my life but there are just things you can do nothing about after they happened. 2) I was on a biz trip in the US and missed Blade Runner 2049. didn't think it was a big deal until I watched it months later on TV. Couldn't helping thinking how I would be totally paralysed by this movie, its sound, its cinematography, its story, its acting, its depth, its inspiration if I have watched it on iMax. I have no doubt if there were chances back I would have watched it in cinema again and again. And by that I would be able to contribute some money for this masterpiece. It won't change the office box result but together we could have told the world that the true art would still be apprecaited and memorized by some people.
